        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Memorandum.<lb/></p>
            <p>New York&#44; Sept. 14&#44; 1890<lb/></p>
            <p>From<lb/>
                The American Hebrew&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>To Dr S. Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>498&#45;500 Third Avenue.<lb/></p>
            <p>Telephone&#58; 243&#44; 39th.<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Mr. Morais&#58;&#45;I have been asked to inquire if you<lb/> have any objection to the printing in The Menorah in<lb/> whole or in part of your &#34;Jew in Italy&#44;&#34; and if there<lb/> are any changes you would like to make in it<lb/> if it is reprinted.  Mr. Peixotto is very sick&#59; in fact&#44;<lb/> his days appear to be numbered&#44; &#38; some of us are arranging<lb/> the matter for the Oct. No.&#44; so we would like to<lb/> hear from you as soon after New Year as you can.<lb/>  I am very sorry you did not send either to us or<lb/> to some other Jewish paper your letter from Emory<lb/> Smith&#44; as its publication first in such a place<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>would have been a service to the journal<lb/> &#38; to the cause itself.<lb/></p>
            <p>Hoping that the coming year may be<lb/> one of peace &#38; prosperity to you &#38; yours&#44; and<lb/> I remain&#44;<lb/> Sincerely yrs<lb/> Philip Cowen<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
